      <text>
        Morning arrives way too early; I didn't really sleep. Scout and I spent most of the night in our damaged corner of the facility, listening to the plants take watch shifts, hearing the occasional creak of unstable structure and wondering when the hostile plants would return.

        Last night, Florence said, clinical and certain—
        "They'll come back today. They're regrouping, analyzing what worked and what didn't. Expect adapted tactics by mid-morning."

        It's mid-morning now, and the facility looks even worse in daylight: outer walls completely destroyed, floor sections collapsed, ceilings damaged, toxic sludge residue everywhere after the hostile incursion. The contracted defensive core is intact but crowded and claustrophobic.

        Everyone is injured and exhausted.

        Runner's vines are shredded in places, leaking sap they can't afford to lose; they're coiled, trying to regenerate. Velvet's growth shows burn marks from corrosive attacks, with sections withered where hostile spores hit—slowly repairing but at a high resource cost. Remedy is depleted—chemical reserves nearly empty, producing compounds only slowly through sheer biological determination. Even Holloway looks drained, their fruiting bodies drooping and bioluminescence dim.

        Florence alone looks alert. Her wheeled platform sits centrally, analyzing the battlefield—because that's what the facility has become.

        Florence states, not to anyone in particular—
        "We need to prepare."

        Holloway asks, still formal and careful but softer than yesterday—
        "For what, specifically?"

        Florence answers, matter-of-fact—
        "They'll probe our weaknesses. Yesterday we contracted to a defendable core—smart move. But that also means we have less space to maneuver. They'll use that. Expect underground assaults targeting our foundation, coordinated surface attacks on multiple sides simultaneously, and probably some tactical surprise we haven't seen yet."

        I mutter—
        "Cheerful."

        [Scout bounces in tired agreement.]

        Runner surfaces slightly, vines shifting, and reports—
        "I've been monitoring underground movement during the night."

        Florence's platform rotates toward Runner. She asks—
        "What did you sense?"

        Runner extends a vine, gesturing toward the eastern section—
        "Hostile roots probing our perimeter. Not attacking—just testing. Mapping our defensive positions."

        Florence asks, genuinely interested—
        "Which positions drew the most attention?"

        Runner gestures again—
        "Here, and here. Also the southwest corner. They spent significant time analyzing the southwest."

        Florence considers the map and says thoughtfully—
        "The southwest is where our life support systems concentrate. If they've identified that…"

        Runner finishes her thought—
        "They'll target it."

        Florence replies—
        "Yes. We need to reinforce—what do you recommend? You know the underground terrain better than I do."
      </text>
