        Wait — did Florence just ask for someone else's opinion?

        Runner's vines shift uncertainly. Runner says, "I... could create a false weak point — make them think the northwest is vulnerable, draw their attention there while we reinforce southwest?"

        Florence's platform shifts forward, what I've learned to interpret as excitement. Florence says, "That's excellent. Underground misdirection — they're learning our patterns, so we feed them false information. Can you make it convincing?"

        Runner says, "If I position damaged root sections deliberately, leak sap in a pattern suggesting structural weakness... yes — it should be convincing."

        Florence says, "*Do it.* And keep monitoring their probing behavior — any tactical intelligence you gather is crucial."

        Runner sounds pleased. "Understood."

        Holloway watches the exchange with cautious curiosity. Florence didn't just accept a suggestion — she actively asked for one.

        Velvet shifts their position, growth rustling. Velvet says, "If we're expecting coordinated surface attacks, my barrier positioning from yesterday won't be enough."

        Florence says, "Agreed. We need—"

        Velvet interrupts, "*Layered defense.* Instead of one thick barrier, multiple thinner layers with gaps between them. Attackers break through the first layer, encounter empty space, then hit a second layer — disrupts their momentum."

        Florence is quiet for a moment; I can practically see her reassessing her entire defensive plan. Florence says slowly, "That changes the whole strategy."

        Velvet asks, "In a bad way?"

        Florence replies, _"In a brilliant way._ Layered defense means we can position countermeasures in the gaps — Remedy's chemicals, Runner's underground interception points. Turn the empty spaces into tactical advantages instead of just barriers. It's... it's better than what I was planning."

        Velvet's growth stills, like they weren't expecting acknowledgment.

        Florence asks, "Can you grow multiple layers with your current resource depletion?"

        Velvet says, "Thinner layers, yes. I'll be spread across more area but each layer is less resource-intensive than one thick wall."

        Florence says, "Do it. And tell me where you're positioning gaps — I need to coordinate Remedy's chemical placements."

        Velvet starts outlining positions. Florence listens intently, adapting her tactical planning in real time to incorporate Velvet's design.

        I'm watching something shift. Not dramatically, not with grand gestures — just... cooperation — actual cooperation.

        ¶

        Scout bounces, observing quietly. They notice it too.

        Remedy shifts forward. Their voice is still reserved, but less cold. Remedy says, "If we're placing chemicals in barrier gaps, I have a suggestion."

        Florence rotates toward them. Florence says, "I'm listening."

        Remedy says, "Normally I deploy defensive compounds — neutralizing agents, protective barriers. But if we know where hostiles will breach, I could prepare aggressive compounds. Turn defense into offense."
      </text>
