        Florence hesitates—thinking, calculating, processing options—then asks, "I don't know. What do you all think?"

        Silence.

        Runner replies, "If they attack before we're ready, we defend with what we have— incomplete preparation is better than no preparation."

        Velvet adds, "We prioritize completing the third barrier layer—that's Kira's primary protection. Chemical traps can wait."

        Remedy counters, "No. Chemical traps in gaps one and two will slow them enough for layer three to finish. I focus on those two zones—abandon the third and fourth."

        Holloway says, "I position near Kira's location for immediate evacuation if needed. We assume incomplete preparation and plan for worst case."

        Florence listens to every voice, every contribution—then synthesizes, "Combined approach. Velvet prioritizes layer three. Remedy focuses on gaps one and two. Runner maintains underground readiness. Holloway stays with Kira. I coordinate response to wherever they attack first—we adapt as needed."

        Everyone moves immediately—not following orders; implementing the agreed strategy.

        I'm pressed against my pillar in the central core with Scout, watching everyone work with focused urgency—twenty minutes, maybe less.

        The facility feels different than yesterday—still desperate, still dangerous, but collaborative.

        Florence wheels toward me and asks, "You okay?"

        I admit, "Scared. But yeah."

        Florence replies, "Good. Fear is appropriate—it keeps you alert. But we'll protect you."

        I say, "I know." I actually believe it—not because Florence is a tactical genius, but because everyone is working together for real.

        Scout bounces bravely—they're scared too, but ready.

        From underground, Runner calls, "They're coming. Movement detected—multiple directions. Coordinated approach."

        Florence's platform straightens and she orders, "Everyone to positions. Adapt as needed. Trust each other's judgment."

        Trust—she actually said "trust."

        The hostile plants are returning—but this time we're ready. Not just coordinated—together.
